</table>
<p>Japanese uses a broad array of honorifics for addressing or referring to people with respect. In <a href="/wiki/Japanese_language" title="Japanese language">Japanese</a>, these forms of address follow a person's name in the manner of a <a href="/wiki/Suffix" title="Suffix">suffix</a>. The most common and well-known <a href="/wiki/Honorific" title="Honorific">honorific</a> outside Japan is <i>san</i>, which semantically coincides roughly with the courtesy titles "Mr.", "Mrs.", and "Ms." in English. Unlike in English, in <b>Japanese honorifics</b> may be attached to surnames, first names, and even professional titles. Other common ones include <i>sama</i>, <i>sensei</i>, <i>kun</i>, and <i>chan</i>.</p>
