<p><a name="References" id="References"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Japanese_honorifics&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: References">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">References</span></h2>
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> In the anime <i><a href="/wiki/Tenchi_Muyo!_Ryo-Ohki" title="Tenchi Muyo! Ryo-Ohki">Tenchi Muyo! Ryo-Ohki</a></i>, the character Mihoshi is addressed by her computer unit as "Mihoshi-dono". Likewise, when used by <a href="/wiki/Himura_Kenshin" title="Himura Kenshin">Himura Kenshin</a> in the anime <i><a href="/wiki/Rurouni_Kenshin" title="Rurouni Kenshin">Rurouni Kenshin</a></i> when referring to women it is intended to show great humility and respect for the addressee.</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> In the anime <i><a href="/wiki/Tenchi_Muyo!_Ryo-Ohki" title="Tenchi Muyo! Ryo-Ohki">Tenchi Muyo! Ryo-Ohki</a></i>, the characters Seto-sama, Zetto and Washu address the main character Tenchi as "Tenchi-dono" out of respect for his great abilities. A more blatant usage is in the anime <i><a href="/wiki/Naruto" title="Naruto">Naruto</a></i> when <a href="/wiki/Third_Hokage" title="Third Hokage" class="mw-redirect">Sarutobi</a> addresses <a href="/wiki/Orochimaru_(Naruto)" title="Orochimaru (Naruto)">Orochimaru</a> disguised as the <a href="/wiki/Land_of_Wind#Kazekage.2C_Fourth" title="Land of Wind" class="mw-redirect">Fourth Kazekage</a> as "Kazekage-dono" out of equality of both being Kage-level ninja.</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFPatrick_McCarthy">Patrick McCarthy. <a href="http://www.fighttimes.com/magazine/magazine.asp?article=293" class="external text" title="http://www.fighttimes.com/magazine/magazine.asp?article=293" rel="nofollow">"Dai Nippon Butokukai"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.fighttimes.com/magazine/magazine.asp?article=293" class="external free" title="http://www.fighttimes.com/magazine/magazine.asp?article=293" rel="nofollow">http://www.fighttimes.com/magazine/magazine.asp?article=293</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-08-25</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Dai+Nippon+Butokukai&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Patrick+McCarthy&amp;rft.au=Patrick+McCarthy&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fighttimes.com%2Fmagazine%2Fmagazine.asp%3Farticle%3D293&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Japanese_honorifics"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> <i>Rin</i> is thought to have been inspired by European girl's names like <i>Katherine</i> and <i>Marilyn</i>; see <a href="http://kotobakai.seesaa.net/article/8173861.html" class="external free" title="http://kotobakai.seesaa.net/article/8173861.html" rel="nofollow">http://kotobakai.seesaa.net/article/8173861.html</a></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>Poser, William J. (1990) "Evidence for Foot Structure in Japanese". Language 66.1.78-105. Reprinted in Natsuko Tsujimura (ed.) <i>Japanese Linguistics: Critical Concepts in Linguistics</i>. Oxford: Routledge, 2005, pp. 159–190.</li>
</ul>
